There are several texts that support communal adjudication,

The statement of ‘Abdullah bin Masud: 

مَا رَءَاهُ المُسْلِمُونَ حَسَنًا فَهُوَ عِنْدَ اللهِ حَسَنٌ
What Muslims view as good is good with Allah.

Supports the idea of communal adjudication, as well as the statement of the Prophet ﷺ, 

لا تجتمع أمتي على الضلالة
My community does not agree on misguidance. 

And his ﷺ statement, 
لمُؤْمِنُ لِلْمُؤْمِنِ كَالبُنْيَانِ، يَشُدُّ بَعْضُهُ بَعْضاً
"The faithful are like (bricks) in a solid structure: they support each other.” 

The Qur’an identifies the community of Muslims as good and a source of benefit, as does the Prophet صلى الله عليه وسلم who said,
 
إن الله تعالى لا يجمع أمتي على ضلالة
Allah, the Most-High, will not unite my community on misguidance

Not only that, but when the Muslim have no muftis, Qadis or Mujahid’s, the community, as a group, fills those voids. Khalil writes 

ولزوجة المفقود الرفع للقاضي والوالي ووالي الماء وإلا فالجماعة المسلمين
The woman whose husband is missing [she has the right to end her marriage] can present her case to a judge, a governor, or a mayor. If she cannot find one of those, then a group of Muslims can assume that responsibility.

Islamic law continues to evolve and serve, even under extreme pressure.

node.text:
It seems some well-intended people confuse an innovation for an act that scholars dispute.

Al-Manawi in Fayd al-Qadir notes that mistake commenting on the position of Sheikh Izi al-Din al-Salam: “A scholar of his stature should not be unaware of that: when all the hadith about wiping the face after dua are joined, they strengthen each other.” 

It is important to leave people alone who are engaged in worship unless one is sure what is happening is incorrect. Scholars agree on the danger of Inadvertently turning people away from worship, yet they differ, based on evidences, on wiping the face after dua.

The statement of ‘Abdullah bin Masud: 

مَا رَءَاهُ المُسْلِمُونَ حَسَنًا فَهُوَ عِنْدَ اللهِ حَسَنٌ
What Muslims view as good is good with Allah.

Supports the idea of communal adjudication, as well as the statement of the Prophet ﷺ, 

لا تجتمع أمتي على الضلالة
My community does not agree on misguidance. 

And his ﷺ statement, 
لمُؤْمِنُ لِلْمُؤْمِنِ كَالبُنْيَانِ، يَشُدُّ بَعْضُهُ بَعْضاً
"The faithful are like (bricks) in a solid structure: they support each other.” 

The Qur’an identifies the community of Muslims as good and a source of benefit, as does the Prophet صلى الله عليه وسلم who said,
 
إن الله تعالى لا يجمع أمتي على ضلالة
Allah, the Most-High, will not unite my community on misguidance

Not only that, but when the Muslim have no muftis, Qadis or Mujahid’s, the community, as a group, fills those voids. Khalil writes 

ولزوجة المفقود الرفع للقاضي والوالي ووالي الماء وإلا فالجماعة المسلمين
The woman whose husband is missing [she has the right to end her marriage] can present her case to a judge, a governor, or a mayor. If she cannot find one of those, then a group of Muslims can assume that responsibility.

Islamic law continues to evolve and serve, even under extreme pressure.
